# Day 11 – CloudWatch Logs (Troubleshooting)

## Goal
Learn how CloudWatch Agent collects logs from EC2 and sends them to CloudWatch.

## What I Tried
- Installed CloudWatch Agent on Ubuntu and Amazon Linux.
- Ran the `amazon-cloudwatch-agent-config-wizard`.
- Created a log group `/ec2/systemlogs`.
- Tried to configure `/var/log/messages` for log collection.

## Issues Faced
- Agent failed to start correctly.
- Log group stayed empty (no logs received).
- Amazon Linux 2023 uses journald, not `/var/log/messages`.
- Wizard repeated questions and caused confusion.

## Lessons Learned
- **Metrics vs Logs**: metrics are numbers (CPU, memory), logs are detailed events.  
- CloudWatch Agent is optional — many companies already have monitoring tools.  
- Even failed setups teach how services run (`systemctl`), how configs are stored (`.json`), and how CloudWatch organizes logs.  
- Troubleshooting is part of real Cloud Support work.

## Reflection
Although the agent didn’t fully work, I understood the flow of logs and the difference between metrics and logs. This day was about troubleshooting and learning, not perfect results.
